IBM History: From Cheese Cutting Machine to Space Flights
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, with its original name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted in 1924 – originally it was a brand used in the branches of Canada and South America.
The base that gave rise to the birth of IBM arises from the merger of four companies that come back to the 1880s.
It possessed inventions such as the famous "chip clock", which allows to control the entrance and exit of employees.
The new company's architect was the businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also presided over his supervisory board.
Flint filed the head of a competitive company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him with the company’s management.
The new leader eclipsed the founder of IBM (Watson's ideas remain the firm base on which corporate culture and identity are supported).
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name indicates, began with the production and sale of all kinds of appliances for business, from meat and cheese cuts to register boxes.
During the first four years Watson led the company, the billing doubled by $9 million and began the company’s great expansion across the continents.
Watson was so crucial for the company that, almost after forty years occupying the chairman's seat, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under its direction, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM staff and computers helped NASA guide flights to space (to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first generation of computers, the series IBM System/360.
The classics "peace", which introduced the computer standard of that time, came to the market with the name of IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which, by its part, acquired the consultancy part of the company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began offering full advice and high added value services.
The strategy that IBM has paid these last three years is the concept of Smarter Planet, i.e., “a smarter planet.”
Its objective is to make a more rational use of technology, although the areas have not yet been planned and the circumstances have not been improved, for example, in relation to transport and city administration.
For the trade sector, IBM recently presented the “Smart Commerce” platform that allows retailers to manage the full trading cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
In 1932, she opened a branch in the former Czechoslovakia, the first country to have it in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today here, the IBM ČR also operates the strategic externalization center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe has is in Prague. Also here there is a world-famous research team that works with voice recognition.
