How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five authorized state travel agencies in the Czech Republic: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies of that time sold in most cases trips only to the socialist block, since trips to the West were very restricted.
Czech tourists were therefore on vacation to the beaches of the RDA (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period comprised between 1962 and 1972, when you could travel to Yugoslavia, however, after the Yugoslav regime slept to the west and the travel of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that citizens of the socialist block (i.e., also the Czechoslovak) were not allowed to travel freely and individually nor even through the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or to the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise, the individual journey was not possible.
Travel agencies offered in those times also travel to the West, but one should put on the tail with a sleeping bag and spend the whole night, or have “good acquaintances” in the agency.
But not everything was won.
The so-called "changing promise" which was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable people", who could not travel at all.
The Czech currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without exchange guarantee, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of the Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there was a large number of cabins and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired.
The way of traveling the Czechs has suffered since 1989 an authentic revolution.
While until 1989 for us was the no longer will pass the holidays in the RDA or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million holidays to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which today we are no longer aware, the fact that to the currently favorite destination, Croatia, until 1989 it could not travel freely, because it was part of Yugoslavia of then.
At the beginning of the 90s the visa exemption was imposed to travel to the neighboring countries of Western Europe, which caused a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, didn’t look tired of the excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, the groups of Checs slept in parks in campaign stores, as our income from then did not allow us to pay for a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Checs of that time was taking food (conserves, embedded, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our living level increased and with it also the average wages, which around 1997 caused an increase in the demand for travel.
With the increase in travel demand, the agencies began, from 1997 regularly, to prepare the trips using charter flights connections, which made the prices of the trips incredibly lower compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of getting discounts for the volume of passengers.
At the end of the 90s of the past century, Czechs already traveled without a visa to almost all developed countries, except the U.S., which made our trips even more simplified.
Another interesting moment in the post-revolutionary tourism history happened in 2000, when, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from Czech Republic to an exotic country was organized, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights starts every year with Czech tourists made distant and warm countries. This winter will already fly directly from Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this time, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. eliminated the visa for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008 the Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, have spent on travel abroad more than 15 thousand Czech crowns per head, including the expenses on the stay site.
