In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds (The triumph of the idiots) on the personal computer wings, and sat for more than an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
At that time they had passed a few years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working intensely in his new computer company NeXT, waiting for the popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of Cringely’s interview was used in Nerds, he said the original of the interview disappeared during his transport.
It was only after Jobs’ death that a full copy of VHS was discovered in the director’s garage.
This file material, slightly re-edited, is the basis of Steve Jobs: The Lost 68-minute interview, which comes to the Landmark cinemas this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate interviews in depth, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
In four different points throughout the interview, there are great silence between the questions and the answers – from 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, where Jobs is clearly sweeping his thoughts, seeking accuracy.
There are also moments when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, where it seems impatient due to Cringely’s questions, pushing him to go faster towards the topics or arguments of greater importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or the iPhone, there is something strangely prophetic in The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies do well and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computer science.
One thing is to read posthumous Jobs’ career reviews, but there’s something raw and inspiring in Jobs that we see here, the dreamer anxious at the edge of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining it all in detail here, it was and did it.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences of The Lost Interview:
How to Learn to Lead a Business:
“Thro the years in business, I always asked, ‘Why do you do things?’ and the answers that give you invariably are, ‘Oh, that’s just the way it’s done.’
No one knows why he does what he does, in business no one thinks about things very deeply.
