The legends about the trap in school and university exams are very widespread.
There have been cases in which teachers have given the exam answers to students in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching the opposite are sending the message that lying and deceiving are acceptable.
How much deception do we find?
On any day, studies show that they can lie anywhere 10 to 200 times.
That is sure, many of those lies are piadous lies.
Another study showed that the strangers lie three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting.
Detecting lies, or “location of lies,” is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a table game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclam: "I have you", the detection of deception is a branch of serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained during the last six decades in prestigious universities that have carried out deep research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that old myths about lies have been rejected.
The liars look in their eyes.
They don’t always tortue, balbucean, ruborize or worry.
It cannot be concluded either that liars are difficult to detect or unmasker.
An trained lies detector can get to the truth learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, the formation of questions and the times.
I spent several years surveying scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and always emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that deception detection is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps to navigate through our complex world – especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviews, or negotiation management.
Good liars have the ability to read others well, making them feel pleasant, managing their own emotions and feeling intuitively how others perceive them.
We know by research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more “self-oriented lies”, while women say more “one-oriented lies” – usually to protect someone’s feelings – that married people lie less frequently to their partners than non-married people (but the lies they usually say tend to be “enormous”).
We also know that if you are perceived as a malicious, others will feel less guilty by lying to you.
How do I know if someone is lying?
First, observe the subject’s usual behavior.
This is called “create a base line.”
It helps to provide reference points to then measure changes.
Observe the subject’s posture, laughter and vocal characteristics.
It’s better to know if someone normally strikes with his foot all the time to not make unfair accusations when he sees his feet strikes in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for deceitful, verbal and non-verbal behavior groups.
Consider these behavioral groups as alarm signals, not as proof of deception.
People who deceive can freeze the upper part of the body by trying to remember their story, they can point their feet to the door, incline towards a exit, change their posture significantly or show a “post-interview dishogo” -- that exaggerated breath of relief and posture change once all the difficult questions have ended.
Often interrogators make false to see that the interview has ended only to look for that post-interview relief.
It also focuses on the subject’s vocabulary.
Scott Peterson put his foot to the bottom and used the past time while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, launching a national search for her.
People who deceive can also use a distancing language: "I didn't have sex with that woman...Mrs. Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of “restrictive language” when he answers a difficult question: “Well... to say truth... to what I... to my understanding.”
This makes the response a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning signal.
There is no magical formula to detect lies, but develop skills to discover deceit is possible.
These skills will improve anyone’s chances to avoid being victimized by the scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
