Climate Adversity Breaks the Economy
During the first year of management of Mario López Valdez, in Sinaloa has increased unemployment and informality, lowered foreign investment and the economy was contracted
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of Government of Mario López Valdez, autodenominated of change, which generated great expectations regarding the advances in the economy, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, there is no growth observed, instead there is a deterioration in the main economic development indicators.
The low temperatures in February, in addition to causing millions of losses for the agricultural sector, limited the possibilities of the state economy to grow, caused a contraction of economic activity in general of 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, justified mainly by the historic fall of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the ICE report, issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, damages occurred in 582,835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 percent suffered total damage and the remaining 21,07 percent had partial damage, the main sinistrated crops were those of vegetables, corn and garbage.
The decline in economic activity has generated, until November, a constant increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography the state unemployment rate during the first three quarters of the year was observed an accelerated growth, since while from January to March 55 thousand 053 Sinaloans were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 per cent of the Economically Active Population, for the second quarter the rate passed to be 5.28 per cent, and between July and September the average continued to increase to 6.19 per cent, a rate that in number of people throws to more than 74 thousand Sinaloans unemployed, an increase relative to the first half of 18 thousand 969 individuals.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, for economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the actions that from the public policy have been carried out.
"What is being seen is an unemployment growth that has to do with several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market for the effects of a resource restriction by the legislation that was approved at the congress to fight money laundering, and for people who catch dollars illegally it is not easy for them to work, invest them and use them in something," he said.
Migration Arrested
López Cervantes pointed out that in the increase in unemployment there is also a demographic factor.
“The number of people who leave the state looking for work abroad, in the United States has been restricted, first by the difficulties to enter, and second because entering already have also many difficulties to find work, that people are staying and is demanding sources of work here in the state, which makes unemployment rise,” he said.
Informality
The analysis of the Sinaloense labour market is worse by considering the high level of informality that predominates among the working conditions, according to the INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the occupied population in the state works without being quoted as a worker before any social security institution.
Together with unemployment and informality, another of the state’s labor payments are low wages, the entity has the lowest wages in the country, according to Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Forecast.
The average monthly income of the Sinaloan workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, much below the national average, located at 7 thousand 375 pesos.
Contracts of IED
Together with the decline of economic activity and the increase in unemployment, during 2011 the largest decline of Foreign Direct Investment in the last 10 years is recorded, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June of the state IED summed $630 thousand 697 which represents a decline of 87.74 percent compared to the $5 million 143 thousand 312 registered during the same period of the previous year.
The Secretariat for Economic Development of the State Government accounts for a total investment of 17 billion 280 million pesos in the year, occurring mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The debt
In front of the economic contraction scenario, the state government requested in July to the state congress the approval of a credit for 3 billion pesos, the same that would be intended for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the purpose of reactivating the economy, the approval of the local congress was for a amount of 2 billion 600 million pesos, and until November they have not observed the benefits of debt in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the business sector, the first year of Government of Mario López Valdés shows a lack of management capacity of the Government.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, expressed that during 2011 he was lacking the harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the government of the state.
“The performance of the economy in Sinaloa during this year has been really very poor, we have to work intensely to recover the ground we lost in this year, in 2012 we have to redouble efforts, failed to align the effort of all and above all the good march already synchronized of this new government team, we hope that the next year will be much better,” he said.
Economic Lentitude
Loredo López said events like ice cream in early year stopped the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
“The low economic flow is a product of several events, including ice cream, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that doesn’t turn back quickly enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in the processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we’re closing very below the expectations we had,” he said.
redefining vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Patronal Confederation of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, said it is necessary to cause the state towards productive activities of greater dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that it has been working, we believe it is necessary to develop a long-term program in which the vocation and economic direction of the state is redefined, because it is important that all the potential of the material and human resource that Sinaloa has is detonated," he said.
Work to do
The president of the Coparmex highlighted the importance of establishing a vision of the future that better covers the efforts of the Government.
"In general terms I would say that the Government has been striving to give good results in different matters, in the field of economic development there are some advances but it is important that a long-term program is developed," he said.
He pointed out that the current administration has shown advances in its way of conducting public policy.
“There are elements that allow to say that the Government is being more inclusive, I can say that there is work done and I think the Government is aware that there is work to do,” he said.
