Court validates "analog apagon" in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analog signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes that the world has suffered in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) dismissed the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the House of Deputies interpelled against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analog shutdown" from 2021 to 2015, by not meeting the eight necessary votes to invalidate it.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed in his attributions by issuing the decree that detailed the actions to follow to concretize the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With that result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic, was dismissed because it did not reach the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to make a statement on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and this remains in force.
The draft sentence, drawn up by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed to declare the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of radio and television matters is a faculty reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and of law reservation.
For the project voted only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree, and by admiting the demands, the minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and of all the actions in it prepared for the digital transition.
The plenary of ministers decided to dismiss also the demand proposed by the Chamber of Deputies, without entering the discussion of the project, also in charge of the minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his intervention, the president said he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure through general rules the measures for the public administration to prepare.
"I also consider that if I did it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," he recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector correspond to the Federal Executive, who has by constitutional mandate, the State rectorate.
The replacement of analog signals by digital is one of the most important changes that the world has suffered in recent years, and it translates into a better use of the radio spectrum, a better quality of the signal and more channels.
It would be to delay the benefits of digitalization, which implies a decision of public interest, which has not only a technical dimension, "because it covers economic, social, political and national security issues."
These questions, he said, "seek the operation of the entire system established, in accordance with the principle of economic rectorate of the State, encompasses a group of attributions that the Constitution leads to the faculty of the State Executive."
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition, and has done it through the Executive, despite having highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, which in some way invades the sphere of competences of the Congress, since it is providing in the administrative sphere the observance of the laws issued by the Legislative, he said.
Analysis of the possibility of a "vote by vote" counting in Michoacán
According to the data drawn by the PREP the difference between the first and second place of the election of governor is just 27 percent, yet without accounting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total acts.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality in terms of the electoral process of this year in Michoacán, where according to the data thrown by the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP) the difference between the first and second place of the election of governor is just 27 percent, yet without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total acts.
In this regard, the president of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), Maria de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, just last November 9, the electoral body approved a series of linearities in order to harmonize local standards with the federal reform in electoral matters.
As it will be remembered, Michoacán did not approve his Political Constitution or his Electoral Code of the State or his Electoral Justice Act, since the Congress of the State approved the reforms shortly before concluding the legal deadline so that they could enter into force in the present electoral process and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication in the deadlines provided for in the Law of the Official Journal of the State, with the argument that he had some objections.
On the 9th of November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Legislative Power and called "invalid and illegal" the vote of the state mandate to the constitutional reforms, since it has no right to "sanction them or vet them."
Interviewed around the possibility of the "vot by vote", Maria de los Ángeles Llanderal explains that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of the IEM will be possible the realization of partial and total countings of the vote by the local electoral body.
In this way, the partial count of votes, of one or more electoral packages, may be given in the cases that: the results of the acts do not coincide; there is no scrutiny and computing act in the file of the box or does not operate in power of the president of the box; or, when there are obvious errors or alterations of the acts.
Furthermore, the total count of the vote received in all the fields of the election may be made when there is an indication that the difference between the presumed winner of the election and the second place in the vote is equal or lower to a percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is the express request of the representative of the party and/or coalition that postponed the second of the indicated candidates.
The total count of the vote may also be made if at the end of the ordinary count it is established that the difference between the presumably winning candidate and the second place is equal or lower to a percentage point, provided that there is the express request of the representative of the political party whose candidate was second, in which case the electoral packages that have been the subject of partial count shall be excluded.
It is worth mentioning that in that situation it is the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP the difference between the first and the second place is just 0.16 per cent, although without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total acts.
