The new Italian government will form on Wednesday.
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has placed that country at the edge of the economic disaster.
The designated Italian Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the Italian president on Wednesday to present the new government that will face a crisis that has placed Italy at the edge of the economic disaster and threatened the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, named on Sunday, will meet on Wednesday with President Giorgio Napolitano to confirm that he can form a government.
It is expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrates, although it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he will present to the president the result of his talks with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
“I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country’s ability to overcome this difficult phase,” the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say that he could form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
“The frame is now well delineated,” he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than usual, while Italy fights a political and financial crisis that has driven its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a hard austerity package required by European leaders to recover the hit confidence in Italy.
Strengthening the pressure on Monti to rush, the unstability of the markets placed the performance of Italian BTP bonds at 10 years above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to be rescued.
Emma Marcegaglia, the leader of the Italian patronal Confindustria, told the press after meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government a lot."
We believe this government is the last opportunity for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Monti's chances of success were prompted considerably by the support of the PDL party of Silvio Berlusconi, whom the crisis forced to resign on Saturday.
“We believe that Professor Monti’s efforts are intended to have a good outcome,” Central Right party secretary Angelino Alfano told the press.
The support of the PDL, the largest party in Italy, is significant because so far many of its members had opposed the Technokratic Government that is forming Monti.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti Government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what will likely be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockade or delay in your efforts could cause a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added pressure by warning that a Monti failure would be a disaster.
Monti began on Monday consultations with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as youth and women’s organizations.
It will end its round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was named on Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely fast transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief breath at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of the Italian debt have now returned to critical levels among the uncertainty about whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of 1.8 trillion euros, would be too much for the current financial defences of the eurozone.
Monti said his government should last until the upcoming elections, scheduled for 2013, despite the generalized predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement the reforms before anticipating the elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist that he should be formed only by technicians, an indication of his repairs before a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources pointed out that mutual confidence and disagreements between the parties are complicating the attempt to include political figures.
