You never repeat the repertoire.
What is this due to?
I think it’s partially because we have nine albums and we can play more than 120 songs and each likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we take a while not to play, that keeps us focused and also keeps us surprised because it reminds us of the reasons why we liked those songs and that we could have forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting to us and, therefore, I think it also makes it more interesting to people.
With this tour, they are celebrating 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve achieved?
Yes and absolutely.
First of all, I think no one of us imagined we would be in a big rock band and having done it for more than 20 years has made it seem like a dream.
We continue to tell our blessings and it excites us so much that we can continue to make music together.
We all love and love to create music.
We are lucky to go to places in the world to which we have always wanted to go.
Things could not be better for us.
What did it mean to you to have been a fundamental part of the rise of the grunge?
