It’s surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and it’s something uncommon.
From time to time, a band emerges from a city, but it’s far more strange when five or ten bands come out from the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year, we were on a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on his tour, so we are lucky to be friends of all of them yet and we are honored to be part of that sound from Seattle that emerged.
It is also very strange that a band like you stay united and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which, by itself, is much longer than many bands last.
First, I think we are all lucky to be still alive, and second, we are all worried about others.
We are all very close friends and, thanks to that, also opened musical avenues that give everyone freedom to experience.
We trust each other with each other’s music and could not be better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been simple; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we have grown, it has been easier to find a balance.
We make sure you don’t be too turning because it’s easy to fall into that game of the big crowds and the people who love your music.
As long as one reminds that people are there for music, that reminds you that you must respect music and what brought it, without becoming famous and a rock star, something that no one of us really interests.
How do you remember your other Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote very good songs and it was something great at the beginning.
We were a band for almost three years and we never released a album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There were many frustrations because it would last so long and the most important thing is that we are still very friends of Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us and when I hear a song or see a photo I think of the incredible person that Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh, talk about music and football and much more.
He was a surprising human being and we missed him.
The national band Las Robertas will be responsible for opening the show in Costa Rica.
