The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it will conduct a research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people, called the 'Genetics of childhood and adolescence obesity' protocol, which will allow to have markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, head of the Unit of Medical Research in Biochemistry of the Hospital of Specialties of the National Medical Center 21st Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students of the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the research is invited to participate in the population whether or not right-handed, go to the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out to minors, every Saturday from 8:00 p.m.
He pointed out that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Ponent Mexico State) and that since October 8, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (Eastern Mexico State).
Once the goal is fulfilled to bring together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue at the Sports Independence Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and the importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and identify in children and young Mexicans risk factors to prevent the appearance of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the 14th of November, the World Diabetes Day was celebrated, he said that the goal is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and heredofamily history of diseases, with the purpose of avoiding risk factors that trigger diseases such as diabetes or renal insufficiency.
It detailed that on Saturday it applies to all participants anthropometric measurements (weight, size, belt circumference), blood pressure taking, determination of glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetic (seeks to identify genes associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López pointed out that this research obeys the concerns of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in minors.
“The 1999 and 2006 health surveys pointed out that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of children, of 77 percent in obesity, and of girls of 47 percent; in terms of overweight also a dramatic rise was observed,” the IMSS specialist said.
He indicated that the justification for the search for the markers arises in the fact that the country’s population differs from others by its genetic history.
He that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent Indian American, 30 percent European and five percent African inheritance and this condition is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that generally, the genetics of obesity translates into the incapacity to burn the excess of energy we consume (calories) and that is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive assessment of the children, which allows to detect whether they present some degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark color plagues (acantosis) in the neck and forearm, which indicate the likelihood of suffering from metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, the doctors deliver it in writing to the parents, to whom each of the measurements and lifestyle changes they need to make to prevent diseases are explained.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic suffering: sedentarism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, staying most of the day sitting in front of the TV and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to the high calorie intake, i.e. the highest consumption of sweetened beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) with high content in fats and proteins and the genetic that is analyzed in this protocol.
Asphalt of the UNAM would avoid backs
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Chemistry Faculty, develops modified asphalt with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions.
If the signs that sends the pavement were addressed, it would not be necessary to repair about 200 thousand baches every season of rain in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher of the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who assured that if the construction and maintenance process of an asphaltic pavement is appropriate, the baches could be reduced in quantity or, even, completely eliminated.
A technological opinion of the backs, dictated in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, gave it to know that the laboratory at its charge develops modified asphalt with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve their performance and, therefore, the formation of baches.
He explained that the asphalt, the heavest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbons molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphaltes, and others of low molecular weight, called maltes, which together give the floor their characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, close to 180 degrees, it is behaved as a liquid, at 120 degrees Celsius its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees Celsius presents a solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes broken.
The above means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but it is changing during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, the chemical engineering specialist warned.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible floor, which consists of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, composed of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that constitutes the folder, he said, is bathed with asphalt.
By transiting the vehicles and generating efforts, this allows the forces to spread very well on the floor.
If it were modified asphalt, it would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt folder, abundantly, a last layer called rotating folder is placed, which is made of a fine stone material, i.e., a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As it’s the layer that will be in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it should have more mechanical strength than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the road.
By being the part of the floor that will receive and spread the efforts, the rolling folder requires, as well, to have the appropriate thickness and the material from which it is made should be cared for.
Climate, especially moisture and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the ground is moisturized, the water is spread inside the folder and it is difficult to get out, this causes a remix of all layers of the floor and, therefore, the formation of baches.
In the process of formation of a bush, he said, the first to go out is the rolling film and only then the asphalt folder is affected, but the damage does not occur instantly, but it is a process that should be addressed to the first signals with appropriate maintenance programs.
The also member of the National System of Researchers explained that the vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of baches and, therefore, the thickness of each of the floor layers should always go in relation to the vehicle load and ensure that it is fulfilled, to prevent that baches form frequently.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on the asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already even in the market and allow to repair the backs with ease and without the need to use high temperatures.
