This is one of the conclusions of an imposing report from the Royal Society of Canada, which included the participation of six experts from various fields, including ethics, legal and medical.
This committee recommends the Government to modify the Criminal Code in such a way that assisted suicide and euthanasia are permitted, when the patient makes such an option and has been judged competent to make the decision.
For the beginning, experts quote a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit that compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
Although Canada occupies the tenth place, the study points out that “the medicalization of death in Canada has generated a culture in which people are afraid to deal with the issue of death.”
With medication or not, 77% of Canadians don’t have access to palliative care, according to experts selected by the Royal Society of Canada.
And, despite the fact that most Canadians want to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying at the hospital.
