In relation to the delicate topic of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report came to conclusions that do not coincide with the posture of the federal government, which has already declared that it does not want to modify the Criminal Code in relation to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or do not constitute a criminal offence, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not caused an abuse of its application, i.e. the use of euthanasia or of assisted suicide with non-competent persons or that they had not given their consent.
Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, said yesterday by teleconference that, on the contrary, more excesses were observed in those countries where euthanasia or assisted suicide have not been legalized.
“Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, although it is clearly illegal.”
“In Canada, assisted suicide is practiced, although it is clearly illegal,” explained Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians in favor of euthanasia
Remember that 85% of Canadians have already spoken for euthanasia, since they think it would allow people whose death is near to relieve their suffering, according to an Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010.
Moreover, 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not make it clear that the lives of elderly or disabled people have less value.
As for the people who have practiced assisted suicide, 41% of respondents think that a trial against them should not be initiated.
In relation to the maintenance or interruption of health care to a patient, the situation is not so clear, according to the authors of the report.
In addition, among its recommendations they suggest that it is indicated in the Criminal Code that the withdrawal of health care, if legally rejected, does not imply a criminal offence.
The Committee of Experts also calls for health professionals to be formed in the duty of respecting the fact that a patient rejects assistance at the end of his life without fear of facing a complaint.
In the field of palliative care, the committee calls for governments, healthcare institutions and doctors to collaborate to ensure the best palliative care, and not only in cases of cancer.
Finally, in relation to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the committee calls for, unless it serves to reduce physical pain, to be considered as euthanasia and to be subject to the same procedures.
