The government of the great social-democratic/Christian coalition that is in power in Austria has decided on Tuesday to include in the Constitution a "golden rule" budgetary to reduce the public deficit and thus avoid a possible degradation of the Austrian sovereign note by credit rating agencies (triple A).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor, Werner Faymann, who announced this decision after a Council of Ministers, when the Austrian public debt reached 74.6%, a figure much higher than the maximum limit of 60% fixed by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly lower than the debt of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
