The Energy Policy:
Facts must be more valuable than dogmas.
If there is a topic that cannot be addressed taking into account short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and the competitiveness of companies.
It is appropriate that a electoral meeting is the time to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if it studies the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, the demographic evolution will mean the duplication of electricity demand before 2050, unless a huge part of the world’s population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the increasing shortage of fossil resources will have to be palliated to continue producing electricity continuously, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to fight climate change, a topic that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident did not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains alone in its decision to give up nuclear energy.
This is not the case of Belgium, which submits its own to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, nor of Switzerland, which only aims to build central power plants of the latest generation.
On the other hand, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, for some examples, continue with determination with their projects.
The United States, on its side, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, restarting the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island crash.
If the German model, based on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, reality goes against such a speech.
The Berlin election will involve an increase in the price of electricity, a greater energy dependence due to the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions due to the construction of gas and coal power plants.
In a few months, the harmful effects will be noticed.
We need to think about the Danish case.
European champion in the wind sector, from which it gets 30% of its electricity, is also one of the great consumers of coal and gas due to wind intermittence; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are, respectively, a 65% and a 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the constance of our energy policy, our neighbors pay an electricity invoice 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy constitutes a key factor of competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction of nuclear energy would imply a strong rise in the price of electricity, which would rest realism to the wonderful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of the French refuse to pay and, in fact, do not manifest opposition in principle to that kind of energy, according to the surveys.
Let’s remember that our country’s energy policy has lost to build an industrial sector with 125,000 director jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Extremely export-oriented, it covers a galaxy of SMEs specialized in international markets and that can create unlocalizable jobs.
If France decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would involve the sacrifice of a large part of those SMEs and the loss of the 6 billion euros annually in French nuclear equipment and services exports.
Which electricist would charge an EPR designed to operate for seventy years, when the manufacturer’s collapse is planned?
To solve the equation of nuclear energy, we must admit that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no devil source.
Areva’s development of low-CO2, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementary character of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a security authority that exercises strict and transparent control of both the existing power plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, of recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with security.
In a half-century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, occurred in normal operating conditions; it did not cause consequences for people or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to the design of the reactor and unforgivable human failures.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two unprecedented natural disasters, which caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to these progress and the cooperation between the security authorities, and the French and German operators and constructors, the EPR presents a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
While all electric actors want to build a power plant, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for the competitors of Areva and EDF, as it would leave them free way to assume the leadership in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is indispensable and legitimate to look for the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let the emotion, dogmas and partisan maneuveres dominate a debate so important for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy applied by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized starting from various points of view: the saturation of the police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "human rights country" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has jumped to the titles, with the Minister of the Interior (see the Libération newspaper of May 23) proclaiming from the past that France "not needs foreign talents, workers or cameras."
However, it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
The question is that, on this topic, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac fixed the direction declaring in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country that has two million immigrant workers", while on the left, the tone fixed Michel Rocard explaining that France "can not take care of all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of the invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish fountains.
On both sides, immigrants are considered a burden for the French economy and society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity with which they act with respect to immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande is limited to include banalities, indicating that co-development will allow to solve the "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be electorally profitable, but economically it comes very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work that summarizes the latest knowledge about immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in the countries that receive immigrants.
The limitation of immigration weakens growth and damages employment.
Fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace national workers, the unqualified, by pressing them to reduce their wages.
But the experience demonstrates that, in reality, immigrants are rather complementary than replacement of national workers and exercises mainly professions in sectors with lack of employment.
Unqualified immigrants work in sectors that do not attract domestic workers and the most qualified in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
Positive Effects on Wages
Similarly as a surgeon would have difficulties to work in a country that lacks anesthetists, complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of these latter to positively influence national wages and employment.
Given the above, Giovanni Peri calculated that an increase of 1% of migration flows implies a long-term real wages rise of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, without taking into account the fact that the diversity that immigrants contribute to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel prizes and companies such as Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are net contribuents to social systems, as they contribute on average 1% of the total budget in European countries.
For example, the International Labour Organization calculates that in Germany an immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (income less expenditure) of 150,000 euros to the public budgets of average throughout his lifetime.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go to search for the growth points that lacked him "with his teeth".
These teeth, which disguised immigrants, had exactly the reverse effect.
