The Nord Stream, the new gateway of Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which communicates directly Western Europe with Russia passing through the Baltic Sea, has already been placed in service.
It needs to supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, has wanted to celebrate the event with great pump.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Head of State and Government, participated on the shores of the Baltic, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, at the inauguration of the Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and their Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have twisted together the wheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas into the Western Europe network.
With this new gas pipeline, every year additional 27.5 million cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive in Western Europe through a first 1.224 km stretch that communicate the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklemburg-Pomerania.
A second tube should be completed by the end of 2012 which will allow to supply a total of 55,000 million cubic meters of gas, i.e. enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, we are already talking about the possibility of building a third tube on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this enormous work presents airs of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will allow gas supplies directly to Germany, avoiding land transit by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
At a time, these two countries lose some of their power: for them it will be harder to influence Russia by threatening it by closing access to the Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the topic is politically delicate.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has achieved greater supply security.
But the price is a weakening of Europe’s energy, since the project has generated a gap between the Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has learned, in just five years, to make its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
“This gas pipeline constitutes a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that connects us organically,” François Fillon confirmed during the opening of the gas pipeline, demonstrating to what point the big gas sector contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles in the faces of Gazprom’s headquarters, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline also implies a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-covered steel to protect it from the anchors of ships.
It is supported at the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m deep.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid mining camps that date from World War II.
“It was necessary to withdraw or destroy a hundred of them, by caution,” said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It is also necessary to extend the measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal serpent that weighs as 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted in all its length: neither by valves nor by maintenance stations.
It was planned a control platform in the waters of Sweden, but the project managers renounced it by seeing that the Swedish people were not very willing to allow a Russian state society to establish permanently in the sea on their coasts.
“In case of failure, we will interrupt the passage of the gas in less than a minute,” says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas pipeline will thus be released to the atmosphere.
But builders consider it unlikely that a flight will occur, since they have predicted joints that, according to the forecasts, will have a flight every 100,000 years.
The control of the state of the gas pipeline is guaranteed by a submarine robot, trapped by a ship, which carries out external inspections, as well as by a device that circulates through the gas pipeline.
With the shape of a pure, it is introduced into the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of a meter, and moves with the gas.
At its arrival, after three full days of journey at a speed of three meters per second, it provides precise data on possible metal deformations.
The gas pipeline has been designed to work for fifty years without the need for any kind of repair.
The circulation of gas is guaranteed simply by pressure.
At the beginning it is 200 bars and at the exit 100 bars.
Five companies have joined their forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of its shares.
It joined the German E.ON and BASF (15,5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a common company, called Nord Stream, responsible for building and exploiting the gas pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zoug, Switzerland, where the taxation is especially favorable.
After that, Gazprom rented the entire gas transport capacity to that company, for a period of twenty-five renewable years.
“Gazprom will pay for its total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is actually transported,” says Jens Müller.
The funding of the construction of the gas pipeline has ended in a 30% with the shareholders’ contribution and in a 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach €7.4 billion for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure they will not exceed their investment, since Gazprom assumes by itself the risk of the expenditure.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pins.
Valves, with a height of 4.5 meters, form the gas output door.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas at arrival, before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
A total capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a brand booklet.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to return people the taste for writing.
It has an adventure air, from hours of writing to the light of a candle.
The Moleskine booklet is easily recognized, with its black rectangular paste, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskine booklets with the current appearance were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch on the market a booklet of design notes, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then the company’s consultant, was responsible for the launch of the new product.
The booklet is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin, which refers to a barnized cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the bankets.
This type of booklet was highly valued by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine has adapted to the current taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of the avant-garde artists until the twentieth century,” says Maria Sebregondi, who since then became responsible for the brand in Mode.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, to reach a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
Far has remained the confidential production of the first years, in which only 3,000 pounds were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It’s hard to determine the buyer’s profile, since the notebook attracts both business men and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cult.
The small Italian company, which had twelve workers at its beginnings, now possesses about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
It distributes its bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops in the city centre, and has learned to impose its identity.
“We’ve adapted to the times and to the need to write, despite the boom of emails,” says Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the “Detour” exhibition where architects or artists expose their own notebook.
In August, he also launched a notebook with leopard tapas, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Using its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has learned to diversify its products: pockets, schedules, bills, computer funds... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that causes envy: in the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th Week for the Employment of Disabled People begins today.
Despite a resolved public policy, applied since 2005, the unemployment rate among people with disabilities doubles the average rate: 19%, against 9% for the entire population.
is disadvantaged?
“No,” says Éric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of disabled people.
“The progress achieved over the past 15 years is considerable.
At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
“There is still a lot to do.”
Unemployed persons with disabilities are still facing numerous obstacles to access employment.
They usually have an older age: 37% are over 50 years old (a 17% average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not completed the bachelor's degree and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is very widespread among them: 53% for disabled people, against 38% of average.
That is, there are numerous issues that especially make it difficult to return to the work world and that “constitute the quid of the problem,” says Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
These are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those that are not mentioned; people’s mentality advances, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre for the Cité pointed out that the surveyed directors have “a low level of knowledge on disabilities,” with a “excessive representation of people in wheelchair, physical or intellectual deficients.”
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are very far from the goal of hiring a 6% of disabled workers, a goal that was set in a law of 1987.
According to the latest available figures, which date from 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
“Now we reach around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting the contributions from companies that do not respect this law.
The test: the number of establishments "submitted to this contribution", like the amount paid out, has decreased between 2007 and 2011, passing from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which increased the contributions, has generated a great pressure for companies,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects a true awareness, among the big groups.”
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of the societies that own between 20 and 49 workers have disabled employees in their staff, compared to 82% of the companies of between 100 and 199 workers.
